o develop their social and human capital. However, she also shows that factors such as neighborhood and domestic violence and the unavailability of social services leave many women without the ability to strategize towards social mobility. Ultimately, Domínguez makes important local and international policy recommendations on issue ranging from public housing to world labor visas, demonstrating how policy can help to improve the lives of these and other low-income people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAcculturationxUnited States. 0aAcculturationzUnited States. 0aChileansxUnited StatesxChilexUnited StatesxElectronic books. 0aChileanszUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxSocial networksxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxSocial networkszUnited States. 0aPolitical refugeesxChile. 0aPolitical refugeeszChile. 0aSocial mobilityxUnited States. 0aSocial mobilityzUnited States. 4aAhead. 4aBoston-area. 4aGetting. 4aLatin-American. 4acompelling. 4ahousing. 4aimmigrant. 4aliving. 4aneighborhoods. 4apublic. 4astories. 4atells. 4awomen. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785072423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814785072.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK